1
00:00:49,683 --> 00:00:53,686
I think the hardest time is
waking up in the morning.

2
00:00:53,687 --> 00:00:57,390
Those first moments
before I remember who I am,

3
00:00:57,391 --> 00:01:00,228
and think instead,
about who I was.

4
00:01:01,695 --> 00:01:04,331
Mom, there's snow on Mount Tom.

5
00:01:04,332 --> 00:01:07,200
It'll still be there
on the weekend.

6
00:01:07,201 --> 00:01:09,369
Don't make me
go to school today.

7
00:01:09,370 --> 00:01:10,804
It's the first day of snow.

8
00:01:13,674 --> 00:01:16,109
There's snow on Mount Tom.

9
00:01:16,110 --> 00:01:19,446
Want to sleep awhile?

10
00:01:19,447 --> 00:01:21,714
Can't be late for the
first day of school.

11
00:01:21,715 --> 00:01:24,117
Everyone will be skiing but me.

12
00:01:24,118 --> 00:01:26,253
Me, too.

13
00:01:26,254 --> 00:01:28,521
I saw Jill's boobies.

14
00:01:28,522 --> 00:01:30,723
Mom? I saw Jill's boobies.

15
00:01:30,724 --> 00:01:33,226
Will you tell Jerry not
to watch me get dressed?

16
00:01:33,227 --> 00:01:35,562
Reverend Byrd called last night

17
00:01:35,563 --> 00:01:37,824
and said you're going to
have a full class this year.

18
00:01:44,238 --> 00:01:46,374
Good morning, children.

19
00:01:49,743 --> 00:01:51,144
Good morning.

20
00:01:51,145 --> 00:01:54,348
I'm Jill Kinmont, your teacher.

21
00:01:57,385 --> 00:01:58,686
Good morning.

22
00:02:03,157 --> 00:02:06,159
So my mother puts me in
the chair in the morning,

23
00:02:06,160 --> 00:02:09,229
and I stay in it all day long

24
00:02:09,230 --> 00:02:10,830
until she takes me out at night.

25
00:02:10,831 --> 00:02:12,565
You stay in it all day?

26
00:02:12,566 --> 00:02:14,601
Yep. Don't you ever
go to the bathroom?

27
00:02:14,602 --> 00:02:16,303
All the time.

28
00:02:16,304 --> 00:02:18,838
You see, I have an
in dwelling catheter.

29
00:02:18,839 --> 00:02:21,341
A tube that goes inside me,

30
00:02:21,342 --> 00:02:23,543
attached to a bag
on the inside of my leg.

31
00:02:23,544 --> 00:02:25,412
Yuck.

32
00:02:25,413 --> 00:02:27,914
There. That's the place.

33
00:02:27,915 --> 00:02:30,817
Isn't it beautiful?

34
00:02:30,818 --> 00:02:32,552
What's the best way to catch it?

35
00:02:32,553 --> 00:02:34,187
Spear it.

36
00:02:34,188 --> 00:02:35,723
Okay. Who can spell spear?

37
00:02:37,325 --> 00:02:38,358
Come on.

38
00:02:38,359 --> 00:02:41,461
First one who gets it,
gets to try for that trout.

39
00:02:41,462 --> 00:02:46,699
S-P-E-E-R.

40
00:02:46,700 --> 00:02:49,836
That's close.
That's almost right.

41
00:02:49,837 --> 00:02:53,306
But it's more like "ear."

42
00:02:53,307 --> 00:02:54,568
Anyone know how to spell ear?

43
00:02:54,942 --> 00:02:56,176
Eddie?

44
00:02:56,777 --> 00:02:59,412
E-A-R?

45
00:02:59,413 --> 00:03:00,547
Right.

46
00:03:00,548 --> 00:03:02,349
So how would you spell spear?

47
00:03:02,350 --> 00:03:03,483
Everybody.

48
00:03:03,484 --> 00:03:07,320
S-P-E-A-R.

49
00:03:07,321 --> 00:03:08,322
Right.

50
00:03:13,261 --> 00:03:15,662
Nope.
Nobody would want to marry you.

51
00:03:15,663 --> 00:03:16,929
Think not?

52
00:03:16,930 --> 00:03:18,865
They would, too.
She's beautiful.

53
00:03:18,866 --> 00:03:21,501
Yeah, but she can't
dance or nothing.

54
00:03:21,502 --> 00:03:23,270
Anybody ever ask you?

55
00:03:23,271 --> 00:03:24,772
Ask me what? To get married.

56
00:03:25,939 --> 00:03:27,274
Who?

57
00:03:27,275 --> 00:03:28,708
You don't know him.

58
00:03:28,709 --> 00:03:30,344
If he asked you,
how come you didn't?

59
00:03:32,012 --> 00:03:33,980
I always think I'm past it.

60
00:03:33,981 --> 00:03:36,816
That it can't hurt me anymore.

61
00:03:36,817 --> 00:03:39,886
Then without warning,
it all comes rushing back.

62
00:03:39,887 --> 00:03:42,689
Here, in Bishop
more than anywhere.

63
00:03:42,690 --> 00:03:44,758
Because I can still look up
and see the snow.

64
00:03:48,262 --> 00:03:50,864
I'm Jill Kinmont and I ski.

65
00:05:17,818 --> 00:05:19,486
There. There he is.

66
00:05:19,487 --> 00:05:21,621
He's the handsomest thing
I've ever seen.

67
00:05:21,622 --> 00:05:23,723
Fastest man on skis
in the world.

68
00:05:23,724 --> 00:05:25,892
"Mad Dog" Buek they call him,
because he's so crazy.

69
00:05:25,893 --> 00:05:27,527
He takes so many chances.

70
00:05:27,528 --> 00:05:28,028
They say he's trying
to kill himself.

71
00:05:28,029 --> 00:05:29,095
Kill himself?

72
00:05:29,096 --> 00:05:30,363
Well, that's what it says.

73
00:05:30,364 --> 00:05:31,931
What if he dies
before we meet him?

74
00:05:31,932 --> 00:05:33,733
What if he kills himself
before we get on the team?

75
00:05:33,734 --> 00:05:34,867
He won't.

76
00:05:34,868 --> 00:05:36,703
What if he does?

77
00:05:36,704 --> 00:05:38,009
Then we don't get to meet him.

78
00:05:39,373 --> 00:05:40,607
What you got?

79
00:05:40,608 --> 00:05:42,074
Nothing. Come on. What you got?

80
00:05:42,075 --> 00:05:44,010
Let me see. What is it?

81
00:05:44,011 --> 00:05:46,546
Mind your own beeswax.
Gimme the magazine, A.J.

82
00:05:46,547 --> 00:05:47,980
It's Dick Buek.

83
00:05:47,981 --> 00:05:50,016
I even got a letter
from him this morning.

84
00:05:50,017 --> 00:05:52,952
Didn't you girls know?
We've been writing for some time.

85
00:05:52,953 --> 00:05:54,521
He says he's looking forward
to meeting me

86
00:05:54,522 --> 00:05:56,022
when I... Make the Olympic Team.

87
00:05:56,023 --> 00:05:58,658
Sure.

88
00:05:58,659 --> 00:06:01,794
Well, anyway, he's too old for me.
He's 21 or 22.

89
00:06:01,795 --> 00:06:04,464
And besides,
I'm in love with someone else, anyway.

90
00:06:04,465 --> 00:06:06,699
Who's the lucky fella?

91
00:06:06,700 --> 00:06:08,135
James Dean.

92
00:06:15,142 --> 00:06:16,777
All right, listen up, everybody.

93
00:06:19,046 --> 00:06:21,548
A.J.?

94
00:06:21,549 --> 00:06:24,484
Okay. We have our first competition
of the year this weekend

95
00:06:24,485 --> 00:06:27,487
or, or next weekend, rather.

96
00:06:27,488 --> 00:06:29,822
Now, I usually just take the
best skiers to these races,

97
00:06:29,823 --> 00:06:31,591
but this time...

98
00:06:31,592 --> 00:06:33,427
I've decided to take everybody.

99
00:06:39,767 --> 00:06:41,968
Herbie Johnson,
keep your hands off me.

100
00:06:41,969 --> 00:06:43,069
I didn't do nothing.

101
00:06:43,070 --> 00:06:44,671
Herbie, take it easy.

102
00:06:44,672 --> 00:06:45,938
What did I do wrong?

103
00:06:45,939 --> 00:06:48,708
As if you didn't know.
You have your hands all over the place.

104
00:06:48,709 --> 00:06:50,910
They are not. They're right
here at the end of my arms.

105
00:06:50,911 --> 00:06:52,979
All right, somebody just trade
places with Jill right now.

106
00:06:52,980 --> 00:06:54,046
I will.

107
00:06:54,047 --> 00:06:55,649
Audra Jo.

108
00:07:15,569 --> 00:07:17,204
It's great. Look at that.

109
00:07:19,673 --> 00:07:21,140
It's fantastic.

110
00:07:21,141 --> 00:07:23,143
A.J., come back
and get your skis.

111
00:07:24,177 --> 00:07:25,177
A.J.?

112
00:07:26,847 --> 00:07:29,782
Herbie.

113
00:07:29,783 --> 00:07:32,251
Herbie tell her to come
back and get her skis.

114
00:07:32,252 --> 00:07:33,687
Now, let's all stick together.

115
00:07:34,254 --> 00:07:35,888
All right.

116
00:07:35,889 --> 00:07:37,957
As far back as I can remember,

117
00:07:37,958 --> 00:07:40,593
all I ever wanted to do was ski.

118
00:07:40,594 --> 00:07:42,094
It wasn't just a sport

119
00:07:42,095 --> 00:07:43,764
it was a way of life.

120
00:07:45,666 --> 00:07:48,134
Our coach was Dave McCoy.

121
00:07:48,135 --> 00:07:51,539
An ex-champion who shaped us
into a top high school team.

122
00:07:59,847 --> 00:08:04,283
Five, four, three, two, one.

123
00:08:04,284 --> 00:08:06,886
Go.

124
00:08:06,887 --> 00:08:10,623
Our toughest competition was
a team from Boulder, Colorado.

125
00:08:10,624 --> 00:08:13,226
Headed by a speed demon,
named Buddy Werner.

126
00:08:29,009 --> 00:08:31,210
In the starting gate,
number 46 Three, two, one.

127
00:08:31,211 --> 00:08:32,429
From Bishop, California. Go!

128
00:08:48,295 --> 00:08:50,563
10 seconds.

129
00:08:50,564 --> 00:08:52,298
Skeeter Werner,
Boulder, Colorado.

130
00:08:52,299 --> 00:08:55,868
Five, four, three, two, one.

131
00:08:55,869 --> 00:08:57,536
Go.

132
00:08:57,537 --> 00:09:02,074
The best skier on the Colorado
girl's team was Skeeter Werner.

133
00:09:02,075 --> 00:09:06,112
And it became a personal battle
to prove which team was best.

134
00:09:06,113 --> 00:09:09,215
14, 10 seconds.
Audra Jo Nicholson, Bishop, California,

135
00:09:09,216 --> 00:09:11,217
wearing number 14. Five, four,

136
00:09:11,218 --> 00:09:13,720
three, two, one.

137
00:09:13,721 --> 00:09:14,755
Go.

138
00:09:16,857 --> 00:09:19,992
This is her second
year of competition.

139
00:09:19,993 --> 00:09:23,196
Last year, finishing fourth in the
finals at Big Bear, California.

140
00:09:28,101 --> 00:09:29,936
Number 89, in the starting gate.

141
00:09:29,937 --> 00:09:33,005
In the starting gate,
Jill Kinmont, number 89.

142
00:09:33,006 --> 00:09:35,642
Ranking first place...

143
00:09:35,643 --> 00:09:37,810
Jill could still take her,
Skeeter only got me by five seconds.

144
00:09:37,811 --> 00:09:38,811
10 seconds.

145
00:09:41,314 --> 00:09:45,818
Five, four, three, two, one.

146
00:09:45,819 --> 00:09:46,819
Go.

147
00:09:50,023 --> 00:09:52,359
Go, Jill. Go.
Go, Jill. Come on do it.

148
00:10:05,773 --> 00:10:09,176
Jill Kinmont, number
89, incompleted run.

149
00:10:16,717 --> 00:10:17,717
Beautiful.

150
00:10:19,386 --> 00:10:20,353
Want me to take your picture?

151
00:10:20,354 --> 00:10:22,054
I bit my tongue.

152
00:10:22,055 --> 00:10:23,882
Shouldn't stick it out
while you're racing.

153
00:10:24,157 --> 00:10:25,424
Want to know why you burned?

154
00:10:25,425 --> 00:10:27,259
My coach will tell me,
thank you.

155
00:10:27,260 --> 00:10:28,995
Skiing is gravity.

156
00:10:28,996 --> 00:10:30,296
Much more powerful than you are.

157
00:10:30,297 --> 00:10:32,037
The less you fight it,
the faster you go.

158
00:10:32,365 --> 00:10:33,866
Do I know you?

159
00:10:33,867 --> 00:10:34,867
No.

160
00:10:35,268 --> 00:10:36,303
Get up.

161
00:10:39,072 --> 00:10:41,073
What are you, a doctor or something?
Nope.

162
00:10:41,074 --> 00:10:43,175
Now, keep your hands
out in front of you.

163
00:10:43,176 --> 00:10:45,311
What's "M.D." stand for?

164
00:10:45,312 --> 00:10:47,379
That's my name. Just...
Just crouch down and stay loose.

165
00:10:47,380 --> 00:10:49,816
Now, gravity works through the hinges.
Right? Mike. Your name's Mike.

166
00:10:49,817 --> 00:10:52,051
Ankles, knees, butt, elbows.
Melvin.

167
00:10:52,052 --> 00:10:54,186
Mark? Maurice? Max? Stick your butt out.
Man, stick it way out.

168
00:10:54,187 --> 00:10:56,289
Make yourself like a bullet...
Hey!

169
00:10:57,691 --> 00:10:58,991
You want to learn to ski or not?

170
00:10:58,992 --> 00:11:00,893
Look, I'm sorry.

171
00:11:00,894 --> 00:11:03,063
I don't take skiing lessons
from just anybody.

172
00:11:05,132 --> 00:11:07,567
I'm Jill Kinmont,
and I just happen to be the best ski...

173
00:11:09,102 --> 00:11:10,236
My God!

174
00:11:10,237 --> 00:11:12,138
You're "Mad Dog" Buek.

175
00:11:12,139 --> 00:11:13,906
We have it confirmed now...

176
00:11:13,907 --> 00:11:15,976
Skeeter and Bud Werner...

177
00:12:17,370 --> 00:12:19,939
I had met Dick Buek.

178
00:12:19,940 --> 00:12:22,975
I thought my life would
never be the same.

179
00:12:22,976 --> 00:12:26,213
But summer came,
and all fantasies had to be put aside.

180
00:12:28,148 --> 00:12:31,317
My family ran a guest ranch
called the Rocking X.

181
00:12:31,318 --> 00:12:34,955
And during the summers,
all of us did our share.

182
00:12:41,361 --> 00:12:43,930
My best friend was
Audra Jo Nicholson

183
00:12:43,931 --> 00:12:45,765
and we were inseparable.

184
00:12:50,237 --> 00:12:51,237
He's adorable.

185
00:12:58,345 --> 00:13:00,479
There was nothing we didn't
know about each other,

186
00:13:00,480 --> 00:13:03,149
no dream we didn't share.

187
00:13:03,150 --> 00:13:06,052
But our biggest dream
was skiing.

188
00:13:06,053 --> 00:13:07,319
And we lived in
the constant hope

189
00:13:07,320 --> 00:13:09,890
of someday making
the Olympic team together.

190
00:13:33,146 --> 00:13:34,146
A.J.?

191
00:13:35,448 --> 00:13:36,583
A.J., are you awake?

192
00:13:39,119 --> 00:13:40,420
Can I talk to you?

193
00:13:41,454 --> 00:13:42,555
I'm beat.

194
00:13:43,556 --> 00:13:45,525
All you have to do is listen.

195
00:13:46,493 --> 00:13:47,494
Okay.

196
00:13:49,997 --> 00:13:52,465
I been thinking about luck.

197
00:13:55,002 --> 00:13:58,271
Wondering why
I'm always so lucky.

198
00:14:00,040 --> 00:14:02,609
Everything that I ever
wanted I always got.

199
00:14:05,946 --> 00:14:07,614
Did you ever feel that way?

200
00:14:08,882 --> 00:14:10,317
Yeah, sometimes.

201
00:14:12,052 --> 00:14:13,153
And...

202
00:14:16,924 --> 00:14:20,192
And I begin to wonder

203
00:14:20,193 --> 00:14:23,430
if maybe I'm just one of those
people that's just born lucky

204
00:14:25,432 --> 00:14:28,200
or if I'm...

205
00:14:28,201 --> 00:14:30,437
Just using up all
my luck at once.

206
00:14:34,407 --> 00:14:35,508
What do you think?

207
00:14:37,911 --> 00:14:40,447
I think... I think I'm sick.

208
00:14:41,181 --> 00:14:42,949
What's wrong?

209
00:14:42,950 --> 00:14:44,551
I got such a headache.

210
00:14:49,156 --> 00:14:50,722
Maybe you just got
too much sun, A.J.

211
00:14:52,459 --> 00:14:54,393
Want some aspirin?

212
00:14:54,394 --> 00:14:57,129
I took some.

213
00:14:57,130 --> 00:14:59,066
I'll bet it's too much sun.

214
00:15:00,067 --> 00:15:01,134
You okay?

215
00:15:02,102 --> 00:15:03,903
Go ahead.

216
00:15:06,573 --> 00:15:08,141
I don't know...

217
00:15:10,710 --> 00:15:13,446
I think I really wonder...

218
00:15:15,215 --> 00:15:16,616
If I'll ever see Dick again.

219
00:15:19,119 --> 00:15:20,320
What d'you think?

220
00:15:24,091 --> 00:15:25,292
Josie?

221
00:15:28,061 --> 00:15:29,061
A.J.?

222
00:15:30,130 --> 00:15:31,463
You okay?

223
00:15:31,464 --> 00:15:32,698
Josie?

224
00:15:32,699 --> 00:15:35,034
Are you all right?

225
00:15:35,035 --> 00:15:36,468
Hey, you guys.
Somebody call a doctor.

226
00:15:36,469 --> 00:15:38,338
Something's wrong with A.J.

227
00:15:43,276 --> 00:15:46,045
Dave, what did the doctor say?

228
00:15:46,046 --> 00:15:49,381
I think it might be best if
you kids just take my car

229
00:15:49,382 --> 00:15:50,513
and go on back. All right?

230
00:15:51,251 --> 00:15:52,452
What is it?

231
00:15:54,721 --> 00:15:56,623
They think it's polio.

232
00:16:01,228 --> 00:16:02,595
You kids go on now.

233
00:16:05,132 --> 00:16:06,133
Coach.

234
00:16:13,740 --> 00:16:17,444
Will...
Will you give her this ring?

235
00:16:18,311 --> 00:16:21,714
And... Tell her I love her.

236
00:16:26,253 --> 00:16:27,253
I do.

237
00:16:29,122 --> 00:16:30,122
Okay.

238
00:17:00,753 --> 00:17:01,754
Josie!

239
00:17:03,456 --> 00:17:05,591
We're going to
the Olympics together.

240
00:17:05,592 --> 00:17:07,593
You're going to be fine.

241
00:17:07,594 --> 00:17:08,638
We're gonna go together.

242
00:17:10,130 --> 00:17:12,831
You're gonna be fine.

243
00:17:12,832 --> 00:17:14,801
You're gonna be fine, Josie.

244
00:17:16,503 --> 00:17:17,670
You'll be fine.

245
00:17:58,678 --> 00:18:00,712
After Josie got sick

246
00:18:00,713 --> 00:18:03,549
I wanted to ski for both of us.

247
00:18:03,550 --> 00:18:06,519
And I worked harder that summer
than I'd ever worked before.

248
00:18:11,824 --> 00:18:14,393
Are you sure it's him?

249
00:18:14,394 --> 00:18:18,330
Positive. Look. He landed his plane
practically right smack in Dave's front yard.

250
00:18:18,331 --> 00:18:20,632
I saw him from the highway.
I thought it was gonna crash.

251
00:18:20,633 --> 00:18:23,402
But by the time I got there,
he was getting out on crutches.

252
00:18:23,403 --> 00:18:25,237
Crutches?

253
00:18:25,238 --> 00:18:27,439
I swear to God,
he was flying a plane on crutches.

254
00:18:27,440 --> 00:18:28,607
Why? His leg.

255
00:18:28,608 --> 00:18:30,876
His broken leg.

256
00:18:30,877 --> 00:18:34,180
Didn't you know?
It was in all the magazines.

257
00:18:34,181 --> 00:18:36,282
He was on his
motorcycle doing 110

258
00:18:36,283 --> 00:18:37,916
ran smack into a camper trailer

259
00:18:37,917 --> 00:18:40,486
flew right through the window
and out the other side.

260
00:18:40,487 --> 00:18:42,588
They thought he was dead.
They even pulled a sheet over his face.

261
00:18:42,589 --> 00:18:43,689
Can you imagine?

262
00:18:43,690 --> 00:18:45,624
I didn't even know.

263
00:18:45,625 --> 00:18:48,361
Well, that's what you get
for being such a hermit.

264
00:18:52,299 --> 00:18:53,632
You better not be kidding
me, Linda.

265
00:18:53,633 --> 00:18:55,534
Kidding? I swear.

266
00:18:55,535 --> 00:18:56,927
Look at the plane,
you dumb-dumb.

267
00:19:09,349 --> 00:19:10,382
Hi, girls.

268
00:19:10,383 --> 00:19:11,551
Hi.

269
00:19:13,453 --> 00:19:14,621
What's up?

270
00:19:18,558 --> 00:19:21,193
We were just on our way to
school, and,

271
00:19:21,194 --> 00:19:23,962
thought we'd stop by and...

272
00:19:23,963 --> 00:19:25,498
See what time practice was.

273
00:19:27,634 --> 00:19:29,835
Same as usual.

274
00:19:29,836 --> 00:19:32,871
Jill, I told you it
was the same as usual.

275
00:19:32,872 --> 00:19:35,708
3.30. I don't know why she
insisted on coming up here.

276
00:19:40,280 --> 00:19:41,647
Hi.

277
00:19:41,648 --> 00:19:43,749
- Excuse me.
- Hi.

278
00:19:43,750 --> 00:19:44,816
I'm Linda Meyers.

279
00:19:44,817 --> 00:19:46,685
Hi, Linda.

280
00:19:46,686 --> 00:19:49,655
I been, reading about you
ever since you started skiing.

281
00:19:49,656 --> 00:19:51,824
And I, wrote you
a letter in the hospital.

282
00:19:55,362 --> 00:19:57,829
This is an old friend of mine.

283
00:19:57,830 --> 00:19:58,931
Old friend of mine, too.

284
00:19:59,632 --> 00:20:01,333
You know her?

285
00:20:01,334 --> 00:20:03,302
Taught her everything she knows.

286
00:20:03,303 --> 00:20:05,904
Now, listen, girls, don't...
Don't, be late to school. All right.

287
00:20:05,905 --> 00:20:08,540
Come on, Jill.
We're gonna be late for school.

288
00:20:08,541 --> 00:20:10,942
You go ahead. I'll
meet you at practice.

289
00:20:10,943 --> 00:20:12,711
What do you mean, go ahead?

290
00:20:12,712 --> 00:20:13,846
Just go ahead.

291
00:20:22,589 --> 00:20:26,392
So...

292
00:20:26,393 --> 00:20:28,427
You want to take
a walk or something?

293
00:20:28,428 --> 00:20:29,428
Okay.

294
00:20:30,029 --> 00:20:31,029
Let's go,

295
00:21:12,472 --> 00:21:14,740
Do you suppose she's
in there with him?

296
00:21:14,741 --> 00:21:16,709
I think we better
call Dave McCoy.

297
00:21:30,457 --> 00:21:31,757
We can get across right here.

298
00:21:31,758 --> 00:21:33,859
You'll never make it.

299
00:21:33,860 --> 00:21:35,927
Race you across.

300
00:21:35,928 --> 00:21:37,997
Why is it you do these things?

301
00:21:39,399 --> 00:21:41,368
You really want to
kill yourself.

302
00:21:45,538 --> 00:21:47,973
I've heard about
the crazy things you do.

303
00:21:47,974 --> 00:21:51,009
Sky diving with parachutes
you find in trash cans.

304
00:21:51,010 --> 00:21:53,012
Riding your motorcycle
like a maniac.

305
00:21:54,681 --> 00:21:56,616
Don't believe
everything you hear.

306
00:21:58,918 --> 00:21:59,985
Why, Dick?

307
00:21:59,986 --> 00:22:01,687
Why what?

308
00:22:01,688 --> 00:22:03,755
Why do you want to die?

309
00:22:03,756 --> 00:22:05,056
You care?

310
00:22:05,057 --> 00:22:06,792
Don't be silly.

311
00:22:06,793 --> 00:22:07,960
I just want to know.

312
00:22:10,096 --> 00:22:11,364
I don't think about that.

313
00:22:20,540 --> 00:22:27,413
So... Here I am, I'm, nothing.

314
00:22:27,414 --> 00:22:29,982
Tenth grade education,
not a decent thought in my head,

315
00:22:31,150 --> 00:22:33,885
but I keep on living.

316
00:22:33,886 --> 00:22:36,923
No matter what I do,
I just get right back up on my feet again.

317
00:22:39,125 --> 00:22:42,461
I don't know why
good people die.

318
00:22:42,462 --> 00:22:44,063
And I just keep on going.

319
00:22:46,833 --> 00:22:48,067
Well, you are good.

320
00:22:49,001 --> 00:22:50,002
You are.

321
00:22:51,704 --> 00:22:53,905
What the hell do you know?

322
00:22:53,906 --> 00:22:55,941
I know I care about you.

323
00:22:55,942 --> 00:22:57,910
So you must be good.

324
00:23:00,747 --> 00:23:02,381
Think I'm funny?

325
00:23:04,751 --> 00:23:05,838
I think you're beautiful.

326
00:23:06,619 --> 00:23:07,754
Me, too.

327
00:23:09,856 --> 00:23:11,090
You, I mean.

328
00:23:26,673 --> 00:23:31,143
Dick... Please stay alive.

329
00:24:03,676 --> 00:24:06,144
Winter, 1955.

330
00:24:06,145 --> 00:24:08,780
The Olympics were
just one year away.

331
00:24:08,781 --> 00:24:10,749
And anyone who wanted to qualify

332
00:24:10,750 --> 00:24:12,151
had to finish the season on top.

333
00:24:13,920 --> 00:24:16,087
- 10 seconds.
- Number 32,

334
00:24:16,088 --> 00:24:18,023
Carol Collingsworth.

335
00:24:18,024 --> 00:24:22,494
Five, four, three, two, one.

336
00:24:22,495 --> 00:24:23,495
Go.

337
00:24:57,864 --> 00:25:00,566
Okay. You can't see very
well, so stay loose,

338
00:25:00,567 --> 00:25:02,267
but be aggressive all the way.
Okay?

339
00:25:02,268 --> 00:25:04,235
10 seconds.

340
00:25:04,236 --> 00:25:08,139
Wearing number 89, Jill Kinmont.

341
00:25:08,140 --> 00:25:11,943
Five, four, three, two, one.

342
00:25:11,944 --> 00:25:13,179
Go.

343
00:25:23,022 --> 00:25:26,892
As the competition got stiffer,
so did my determination to win.

344
00:25:26,893 --> 00:25:31,830
I swept the regionals, winning more trophies
than had ever been won in a single year.

345
00:25:31,831 --> 00:25:33,700
And number 89 became
the number to watch.

346
00:25:49,348 --> 00:25:50,348
Excuse me.

347
00:25:53,019 --> 00:25:55,921
Well... Smooth. Very smooth.

348
00:25:55,922 --> 00:25:57,756
We need a time on that now.

349
00:25:57,757 --> 00:25:59,024
Hey, Buddy, how about
putting your arms around her?

350
00:25:59,025 --> 00:26:00,592
You better ask her first.

351
00:26:00,593 --> 00:26:02,561
The winner Is Jill Kinmont.

352
00:26:12,238 --> 00:26:14,372
In that Incredible year.

353
00:26:14,373 --> 00:26:17,342
Buddy Werner had a winning
streak as lucky as mine.

354
00:26:17,343 --> 00:26:20,747
And everywhere we went,
people were trying to start a romance.

355
00:26:23,182 --> 00:26:25,984
But I was still thinking
about Dick Buek

356
00:26:25,985 --> 00:26:27,754
and all that winter
I looked for him.

357
00:26:53,379 --> 00:26:54,814
Hey, Dick... Hey.

358
00:26:59,085 --> 00:27:01,720
Buddy, look who's here.
Dick Buek.

359
00:27:01,721 --> 00:27:03,221
Who's that blonde with him?

360
00:27:03,222 --> 00:27:07,058
Must be Sigrid Halvorson.
They say they're engaged.

361
00:27:07,059 --> 00:27:09,160
Look who's here. It's Dick Buek.

362
00:27:09,161 --> 00:27:10,629
Hey, how're you doing?

363
00:27:14,667 --> 00:27:15,934
Hey, Dick.
Hey, how're you doing?

364
00:27:15,935 --> 00:27:17,769
All right.
Hey, how'd you break your arm?

365
00:27:17,770 --> 00:27:19,672
Dancing with a very heavy girl.

366
00:27:28,981 --> 00:27:30,649
I know you, right?

367
00:27:30,917 --> 00:27:32,684
Yeah.

368
00:27:32,685 --> 00:27:33,886
Hey, Buddy. Yeah.

369
00:27:35,087 --> 00:27:37,656
I want to introduce
you to my fiancee.

370
00:27:41,928 --> 00:27:44,129
Hey, Dick Buek. How are you?
How've you been?

371
00:27:44,130 --> 00:27:46,464
Remember Charlie from
Lake Placid last winter?

372
00:27:46,465 --> 00:27:48,900
Come on, I'll buy you a beer.
Let's go.

373
00:27:48,901 --> 00:27:50,771
Come on. You can talk
to these people later.

374
00:28:14,794 --> 00:28:16,729
Hey... Don't.

375
00:28:21,333 --> 00:28:23,035
Hey, whatever's at...

376
00:28:26,773 --> 00:28:29,008
Whatever's wrong,
I'd like to help.

377
00:29:13,252 --> 00:29:14,921
Good run.

378
00:29:18,324 --> 00:29:21,059
All right, take it easy this time.
Now, you're way ahead. Right?

379
00:29:21,060 --> 00:29:22,961
So don't go for any records.

380
00:29:22,962 --> 00:29:26,331
Now remember that,
tree jump, right?

381
00:29:26,332 --> 00:29:29,134
All right, look good. Have fun.
Hold on to that lead.

382
00:29:29,135 --> 00:29:30,435
89, 10 seconds.

383
00:29:30,436 --> 00:29:33,371
At the starting gate,
Jill Kinmont.

384
00:29:33,372 --> 00:29:36,274
Five, four, three,
...skier of the year.

385
00:29:36,275 --> 00:29:38,544
Two, one. Go.

386
00:29:42,181 --> 00:29:44,449
With the season
drawing to a close,

387
00:29:44,450 --> 00:29:47,518
Buddy and I were invited
to a special training camp,

388
00:29:47,519 --> 00:29:51,256
preparing ourselves for the
last big race of the year.

389
00:29:51,257 --> 00:29:54,259
It was called the Snow Cup,
held in Alta, Utah.

390
00:29:54,260 --> 00:29:56,896
And if I won there,
I'd qualify for the Olympics.

391
00:30:21,153 --> 00:30:23,155
Come on, Jill,
quit fooling around.

392
00:31:14,974 --> 00:31:16,642
No, you're on your own. Come on!

393
00:31:22,614 --> 00:31:26,417
February 1st, 1955.

394
00:31:26,418 --> 00:31:29,120
The Snow Cup is
only a few days away.

395
00:31:29,121 --> 00:31:32,057
And the experts were betting
on both of us to win.

396
00:31:32,058 --> 00:31:34,225
You and Buddy going to
the Olympics together?

397
00:31:34,226 --> 00:31:35,927
Did you ever ski each
other off the slopes?

398
00:31:35,928 --> 00:31:38,930
Only on tournaments sometimes.

399
00:31:38,931 --> 00:31:40,453
What if you don't
make it this year?

400
00:31:44,670 --> 00:31:47,106
That was a beautiful run, Jill.

401
00:31:50,342 --> 00:31:52,995
If you win the Snow Cup are you
certified in the Olympic Team?

402
00:31:58,350 --> 00:32:02,653
The arrival of flight 22 from
Los Angeles to Salt Lake City.

403
00:32:02,654 --> 00:32:05,924
Those waiting for arriving
passengers proceed...

404
00:32:12,664 --> 00:32:15,266
What's the toughest competition
that you think you'll have?

405
00:32:15,267 --> 00:32:17,668
How do you think
she's gonna do at Alta?

406
00:32:17,669 --> 00:32:19,670
Are you confident that you
can make it to the Olympics?

407
00:32:19,671 --> 00:32:21,639
There are a lot of people
counting on you for Alda.

408
00:32:21,640 --> 00:32:22,741
This is the big one?

409
00:32:33,085 --> 00:32:35,253
It's divided
into three sections.

410
00:32:35,254 --> 00:32:37,655
You got a fairly easy start,

411
00:32:37,656 --> 00:32:39,357
but you're going to be
building up a lot of speed

412
00:32:39,358 --> 00:32:40,992
coming into that middle section.

413
00:32:40,993 --> 00:32:43,394
That's the gulley,
the one they call the corkscrew.

414
00:32:43,395 --> 00:32:44,395
It's over there.

415
00:32:46,432 --> 00:32:50,135
Then a fairly easy valley
and you're on home.

416
00:32:50,136 --> 00:32:54,005
But the race is gonna be won or lost
right here. Right here in the corkscrew.

417
00:32:54,006 --> 00:32:56,574
There's a sharp...
Sharp rise just ahead of it.

418
00:32:56,575 --> 00:32:59,344
So if you come into it too fast,
you're gonna go straight up.

419
00:32:59,345 --> 00:33:00,345
So check there. Right?

420
00:33:00,579 --> 00:33:02,313
Right.

421
00:33:02,314 --> 00:33:04,715
Wait a minute.
There's Andrea Meade Lawrence.

422
00:33:04,716 --> 00:33:06,499
She's checking.
She's slowing down. Right?

423
00:33:11,190 --> 00:33:12,423
All right, now,
that's about perfect.

424
00:33:12,424 --> 00:33:14,659
See, 'cause she lost a little
time, but she gained control.

425
00:33:14,660 --> 00:33:15,794
Do you understand?

426
00:33:18,364 --> 00:33:22,333
Go ahead and, take your practice run.
All right?

427
00:33:22,334 --> 00:33:25,303
My main competition here was
a girl named Andy Lawrence.

428
00:33:25,304 --> 00:33:27,372
A top Eastern skier.

429
00:33:27,373 --> 00:33:30,375
Who needed to win this
race as much as I did.

430
00:33:30,376 --> 00:33:32,643
But after watching
her practice run

431
00:33:32,644 --> 00:33:34,679
I knew she could be beaten.

432
00:33:34,680 --> 00:33:37,048
She was slowing down
at the corkscrew

433
00:33:37,049 --> 00:33:38,528
and this is where
I could take her.

434
00:33:55,367 --> 00:33:56,401
Jill!

435
00:33:56,402 --> 00:33:57,536
Buddy.

436
00:34:03,842 --> 00:34:05,576
Just wanted to say good luck.

437
00:34:05,577 --> 00:34:07,045
Good luck to you.

438
00:34:09,381 --> 00:34:10,681
Here.

439
00:34:10,682 --> 00:34:12,283
What is it?
I want you to have it.

440
00:34:12,284 --> 00:34:13,518
What?

441
00:34:13,519 --> 00:34:15,421
St. Christopher's.
I wear it for luck.

442
00:34:17,589 --> 00:34:20,225
I gotta go. Yeah, Jill,

443
00:34:20,226 --> 00:34:21,792
I want to go to the
Olympics married.

444
00:34:22,294 --> 00:34:23,528
To me?

445
00:34:23,529 --> 00:34:25,396
Who do you think?

446
00:34:25,397 --> 00:34:27,099
I don't know.
I'm a nervous wreck.

447
00:34:30,469 --> 00:34:31,603
I really got to go.

448
00:34:32,404 --> 00:34:33,672
I love you, honey.

449
00:34:35,307 --> 00:34:36,307
Me, too, you.

450
00:34:38,210 --> 00:34:39,444
We got a date at the
bottom, right?

451
00:34:39,445 --> 00:34:41,212
Right.

452
00:34:41,213 --> 00:34:42,247
We'll talk about it there.
Okay? Right.

453
00:34:42,248 --> 00:34:43,349
Go get 'em.

454
00:34:45,884 --> 00:34:48,853
Number 14 in the men's division,

455
00:34:48,854 --> 00:34:52,158
Bobby Werner,
making his first run.

456
00:35:31,597 --> 00:35:33,232
Hey, look at that.

457
00:35:37,503 --> 00:35:38,869
Look right and left.

458
00:35:38,870 --> 00:35:41,372
Carpenter and Walsh have
already broken their records.

459
00:35:41,373 --> 00:35:43,508
And the two main contenders,
Andrea Meade Lawrence

460
00:35:43,509 --> 00:35:46,344
and Jill Kinmont
